      {
        "id": "1ccd3b99a609fcd504de5aa16b3ca9e218408e63",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-02 18:55:21.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\n(8 comments)\n\nMy main concern is the intertwining between junits and codes.   While easier to hack junits and get them to work by adding what is needed to code and poms.   In a real lab environment, it is more challenging, loading control loops dynamically, besides it will increase loading up a control loop at runtime, and could create a jar hell due to transitive versions of dependencies being fetched from maven underneath and relying on JVM resolution in a way that we don't have good control over with.   This affects pdp-d but also the brms gw, as they put together the rules jar.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "94017e99a1ab479cebe98874d481fe99b21615f2",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
          "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pd1248@att.com",
          "username": "pdragosh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-04 11:41:12.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "c95b047b49e6ae537ae3fc04fb25dbe1c78df372",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-04 15:15:33.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nNot sure ..  In any case, I am a bit uneasy overall since the \"junit\"  work mostly affects the non-test code .. 4 \"src/main/java\" files and only 1 \"src/main/test\".   h2 is embedded in the \"production\" persistence.xml, and there is a System property switch deciding which one to use.\n\nI have concerns abut the base code too.  We need an user story here.   I don't see how this will work in a real environment.   I see for example that user name and passwords are hardcoded in the persistence.xml for the database, and guard module and eventmanager use the eclipse persistence libraries in different versions.   I also questions why not all DB operations are delegated to the guard through some interface instead of having persistence.xml almost identical in guard and eventmanager.\n\nFor resolution of this code inspection, I would expect not leakage or minimum leakage from testing code into production code.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "93d3af326cf7c907c8df081ea3ec74969b1ba5a6",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1759,
          "name": "Temoc Rodriguez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "cr056n@att.com",
          "username": "cr056n"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-09-05 16:12:11.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(7 comments)\n\nJorge, the reason java code is changed more than junit code is that the drl calls the \"production\" code, the junit does not. So there is no good unobtrusive way to specify that it is running a test as far as I know. There can be a meeting to clarify all the concerns.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
